1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,980
Today we dive into a truly incredible investigation conducted by economist Alberto

2
00:00:04,980 --> 00:00:06,560
Alesina and Sottim.

3
00:00:06,560 --> 00:00:11,419
It is an analysis that reveals a link that is nothing short of unexpected between family affection,

4
00:00:11,419 --> 00:00:15,759
our most deep-rooted cultural values, and labor market laws.

5
00:00:15,759 --> 00:00:20,960
In short, a completely new and decidedly fascinating perspective for understanding the

6
00:00:20,960 --> 00:00:23,160
economic choices of nations.

7
00:00:23,160 --> 00:00:28,519
Let's start immediately with a paradox, a real brain-teaser that has baffled economists

8
00:00:28,519 --> 00:00:29,519
for decades.

9
00:00:29,679 --> 00:00:34,640
It is a fact that rigidly regulated labor markets tend to generate

10
00:00:34,640 --> 00:00:39,679
higher unemployment and on average lower incomes compared to flexible ones.

11
00:00:39,679 --> 00:00:41,039
And we are with you so far.

12
00:00:41,039 --> 00:00:46,480
But then, despite this obvious macroeconomic inefficiency, why do entire societies,

13
00:00:46,480 --> 00:00:51,200
especially here in Europe, continue to vote with conviction to maintain these rigid

14
00:00:51,200 --> 00:00:53,519
job protection laws?

15
00:00:53,519 --> 00:00:55,920
It almost seems like an absurdity, don't you think?

16
00:00:56,000 --> 00:01:02,000
Okay, let's get to the heart of the matter and compare these two opposite economic models.

17
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:07,760
On one hand, we have the flexible labor market, a system that rewards efficiency,

18
00:01:07,760 --> 00:01:11,359
sure, but which requires very high geographical mobility.

19
00:01:11,359 --> 00:01:15,760
In practice, you must always be ready to pack your bags to chase the best

20
00:01:15,760 --> 00:01:18,960
opportunities, receiving higher incomes in return.

21
00:01:18,960 --> 00:01:21,920
On the other hand, there is the rigid labor market.

22
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:27,200
This model boasts high minimum wages and very strong protections against layoffs,

23
00:01:27,200 --> 00:01:30,719
allowing workers to stay exactly where they were born.

24
00:01:30,719 --> 00:01:35,200
The collective price to pay, however, is higher structural unemployment

25
00:01:35,200 --> 00:01:37,439
and lower overall salaries.

26
00:01:37,439 --> 00:01:42,799
So the mystery remains: why on earth would anyone choose the option that ultimately pays less?

27
00:01:42,799 --> 00:01:47,840
Well, the answer lies in an absolutely unexpected culprit:

28
00:01:47,840 --> 00:01:50,000
the strength of family ties.

29
00:01:50,079 --> 00:01:54,159
It is almost funny to think about, but the custom of adult children continuing to live under the same

30
00:01:54,159 --> 00:01:58,719
roof as their parents literally shapes a nation's economic policy.

31
00:01:58,719 --> 00:02:03,519
Data from the World Values Survey are clear: family attachment manages to predict,

32
00:02:03,519 --> 00:02:08,000
with almost infallible precision, the type of labor market a given society

33
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:09,280
will end up adopting.

34
00:02:09,280 --> 00:02:12,879
Let's see exactly how this chain reaction works step by step.

35
00:02:12,879 --> 00:02:17,920
It all begins in Phase 1, within a culture that places immense value on being united as a family.

36
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:21,360
This leads directly to Phase 2: geographical immobility.

37
00:02:21,360 --> 00:02:25,600
Moving away from loved ones has too high an emotional cost—a real wrench.

38
00:02:25,600 --> 00:02:29,440
Consequently, when workers avoid moving, we enter Phase 3,

39
00:02:29,440 --> 00:02:32,800
in which local businesses acquire disproportionate market power.

40
00:02:32,800 --> 00:02:37,040
And finally, we reach Phase 4: to defend themselves and balance the overwhelming power of companies,

41
00:02:37,040 --> 00:02:41,760
citizens go to the polls and loudly demand that the state intervene to regulate labor.

42
00:02:41,760 --> 00:02:47,680
This phenomenon translates into a concept that economists call monopsony power.

43
00:02:47,760 --> 00:02:50,719
It sounds like a very complicated word, but in reality, it's simple.

44
00:02:50,719 --> 00:02:55,439
If in a monopoly there is only one seller, in a monopsony there is only one buyer.

45
00:02:55,439 --> 00:03:00,159
In this scenario, a local company finds itself being the only true buyer of the time

46
00:03:00,159 --> 00:03:04,240
and skills of workers who, in fact, have no intention of moving.

47
00:03:04,240 --> 00:03:08,319
It's a sort of trap: knowing very well that an employee would never pack

48
00:03:08,319 --> 00:10:05,560
their bags to avoid leaving their family,

49
00:10:10,560 --> 00:03:13,600
the company can afford to impose very low wages,

50
00:10:13,600 --> 00:03:16,960
with the certainty that that worker is going nowhere.

51
00:10:16,960 --> 00:03:19,360
And this is where the real insight comes in.

52
00:03:19,360 --> 00:03:22,159
Summarized in this quote from the researchers:

53
00:03:22,159 --> 00:03:26,080
"To limit corporate rents and to avoid moving,

54
00:03:26,080 --> 00:03:31,840
individuals with strong family ties rationally choose regulated labor markets."

55
00:03:31,840 --> 00:03:34,000
Exactly, rationally.

56
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:37,200
Demanding guaranteed minimum wages or obstructing layoffs

57
00:03:37,200 --> 00:03:40,240
is not at all a symptom of economic illiteracy.

58
00:03:40,240 --> 00:03:44,400
On the contrary, it is a brilliant and absolutely conscious defense mechanism

59
00:03:44,400 --> 00:03:47,439
to neutralize the blackmail of corporate monopsony,

60
00:03:47,439 --> 00:03:50,560
while simultaneously managing to remain close to one's family.

61
00:03:50,560 --> 00:03:53,840
Analyzing global data, the differences are staggering.

62
00:03:53,840 --> 00:03:56,000
Take the nations of Mediterranean Europe,

63
00:03:56,000 --> 00:03:58,080
deeply family-oriented cultures,

64
00:03:58,080 --> 00:04:00,560
where leaving home late is practically the norm.

65
00:04:00,560 --> 00:04:03,439
There, regulation levels are very high.

66
00:04:03,439 --> 00:04:07,200
On the contrary, if we look at Anglo-Saxon or Nordic countries,

67
00:04:07,200 --> 00:04:11,520
where independence and early departure from the family nest are central values,

68
00:04:11,520 --> 00:04:15,520
we find drastically lower labor market rigidity indices.

69
00:04:15,520 --> 00:04:17,519
Now, someone might object:

70
00:04:17,519 --> 00:04:21,600
but how can we be sure it's really the fault of cultural values

71
00:04:21,600 --> 00:04:24,960
and not perhaps geography or the government in office?

72
00:04:24,960 --> 00:04:28,960
To overcome this methodological doubt, the researchers found a perfect

73
00:04:28,960 --> 00:04:33,519
and unassailable control group: second-generation immigrants in the United States.

74
00:04:33,519 --> 00:04:36,000
We are talking about people born and raised in America,

75
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:39,199
who move every single day in the exact same market,

76
00:04:39,199 --> 00:04:42,879
subject to the same federal laws and the same institutions.

77
00:04:42,879 --> 00:04:47,120
The only thing that distinguishes them is the cultural background inherited from their parents.

78
00:04:47,120 --> 00:04:52,480
Well, translating these complex econometric formulas into everyday reality,

79
00:04:52,480 --> 00:04:54,480
the results are breathtaking.

80
00:04:54,480 --> 00:04:58,319
Even if immersed in the same, identical American market,

81
00:04:58,319 --> 00:05:01,599
it is the culture of origin that dictates the law on economic destinies.

82
00:05:01,599 --> 00:05:07,279
Immigrants from cultures with strong family ties tend not to move for work,

83
00:05:07,360 --> 00:05:10,160
face significantly higher unemployment rates,

84
00:05:10,160 --> 00:05:13,680
and end up having lower salaries compared to their fellow citizens

85
00:05:13,680 --> 00:05:18,400
who come from cultures where family cohesion is experienced in a less binding way.

86
00:05:18,400 --> 00:05:23,680
There is one number in particular that helps us visualize the scope of all this: 7%.

87
00:05:23,680 --> 00:05:28,640
It is the exact percentage drop in geographical mobility among second-generation immigrants,

88
00:05:28,640 --> 00:05:34,160
in the face of an increase of just one standard deviation in the strength of family ties from the country of origin.

89
00:05:34,240 --> 00:05:40,320
In short, an invisible but very powerful attachment to one's roots literally and physically slows down

90
00:05:40,320 --> 00:05:42,960
the search for the best job around the country.

91
00:05:42,960 --> 00:05:47,280
And perhaps the craziest thing is that not only economic outcomes are passed down,

92
00:05:47,280 --> 00:05:51,280
but the political demand for state intervention is inherited as well.

93
00:05:51,280 --> 00:05:56,960
Surveys show that these children of immigrants maintain a far higher than average desire

94
00:05:56,960 --> 00:05:58,960
to have a secure job.

95
00:05:58,960 --> 00:06:02,320
They are in favor of state bailouts for declining industries

96
00:06:02,319 --> 00:06:07,279
and have an unwavering faith that it should be the government that regulates wages.

97
00:06:07,279 --> 00:06:13,120
At this point, the most classic of dilemmas arises spontaneously, a true philosophical question.

98
00:06:13,120 --> 00:06:18,399
Is it state laws and institutions that, over time, shape the culture of a people,

99
00:06:18,399 --> 00:06:23,600
or the deep culture of a society that gives shape to its institutions?

100
00:06:23,600 --> 00:06:28,719
What emerges from these studies is the existence of a true continuous feedback loop,

101
00:06:28,720 --> 00:06:32,560
a circle in which the education of children and the economic structure of the nation

102
00:06:32,560 --> 00:06:34,640
influence each other endlessly.

103
00:06:34,640 --> 00:06:40,480
So the crucial point is that societies end up coordinating on two parallel tracks,

104
00:06:40,480 --> 00:06:46,320
two self-sustaining models, or to use a technical term, multiple equilibria.

105
00:06:46,320 --> 00:06:51,280
With weak family ties, a very free market takes over, a laissez-faire approach,

106
00:06:51,280 --> 00:06:53,600
where absolute independence is preached.

107
00:06:53,680 --> 00:06:58,340
With strong ties, however, the market becomes structurally rigid and the

108
00:06:58,340 --> 00:07:04,160
young are taught to rely on the family safety net—two completely different ways of living.

109
00:07:04,160 --> 00:07:10,000
And to understand how powerful this force is, we have to take a long leap back into history.

110
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:14,240
This study demonstrates an absolutely staggering persistence over time.

111
00:07:14,240 --> 00:07:18,720
We start from regional family structures, born no less than in the Middle Ages.

112
00:07:18,800 --> 00:07:23,920
We pass through the values packed in the suitcases of emigrants bound for America before World War II

113
00:07:23,920 --> 00:07:26,600
and arrive straight to the present day.

114
00:07:26,600 --> 00:07:32,040
Surprisingly, values from distant eras are still able to accurately predict how much

115
00:07:32,040 --> 00:07:34,400
labor rigidity we demand today.

116
00:07:34,400 --> 00:07:41,080
Who would have ever thought that the family dynamics of the Middle Ages would dictate the labor rules of the twenty-first century?

117
00:07:41,080 --> 00:07:45,920
Exactly so: the classifications of historian Emmanuel Todd show us that the old

118
00:07:45,920 --> 00:07:52,120
nuclear and independent families left a preference for super-flexible markets as their legacy.

119
00:07:52,120 --> 00:07:57,920
Conversely, the communal-style medieval family, typically authoritarian, where children,

120
00:07:57,920 --> 00:08:01,720
wives, and grandchildren all continued to live under the patriarch's roof,

121
00:08:01,720 --> 00:08:06,319
well, that is reflected today in a citizenry that demands ironclad protection from the state.

122
00:08:06,319 --> 00:08:10,720
And there is a crazy statistic to confirm it: a huge 19%.

123
00:08:10,720 --> 00:08:17,920
Today, people living in regions that centuries and centuries ago were dominated by those authoritarian and communal family dynamics

124
00:08:17,920 --> 00:08:24,320
are 19% more likely to demand that the government intervene to protect jobs.

125
00:08:24,320 --> 00:08:30,920
It's almost as if the ghost of the ancient patriarch were there, invisible, guiding the hand of the contemporary voter.

126
00:08:30,920 --> 00:08:34,519
Summing up this whole incredible and impartial analysis,

127
00:08:34,519 --> 00:08:38,720
labor laws are rooted in a very deep cultural ground.

128
00:08:38,720 --> 00:08:42,320
When attachment to family generates geographical immobility,

129
00:08:42,320 --> 00:08:45,920
companies automatically gain enormous monopsony power.

130
00:08:45,920 --> 00:08:49,920
Consequently, requesting state intervention is not an illogical slip-up,

131
00:08:49,920 --> 00:08:53,320
but a hyper-rational defense to protect the unity of affections.

132
00:08:53,320 --> 00:08:58,120
In short, what is coldly dismissed as inefficiency in economics textbooks

133
00:08:58,120 --> 00:09:01,120
is in reality often a very specific social compromise,

134
00:09:01,120 --> 00:09:03,320
chosen entirely consciously.

135
00:09:03,320 --> 00:09:07,320
Which leaves us with a final, very, very deep question,

136
00:09:07,320 --> 00:09:09,920
that goes far beyond mere economic calculations.

137
00:09:09,920 --> 00:09:13,120
Considering all this, does maximizing at all costs

138
00:09:13,120 --> 00:09:16,120
absolute economic efficiency and flexibility

139
00:09:16,120 --> 00:09:20,120
really worth the price of having a geographically fragmented family?

140
00:09:20,120 --> 00:09:24,520
Deep down, every society continuously makes this silent choice:

141
00:09:24,520 --> 00:09:28,320
optimize pure wealth or protect the closeness of bonds.

142
00:09:28,320 --> 00:09:30,520
It is a giant invisible compromise

143
00:09:30,520 --> 00:09:34,320
that every day shapes the world in which we all live and work.

144
00:09:34,320 --> 00:09:35,720
What is the right path?

145
00:09:35,720 --> 00:09:38,120
It is certainly a great food for thought.